text: Thank you so much. We will be back soon now with people connecting to the keynote of Jillian, Translating Activism into Political Action is a Theme, How to Transport Online and Offline Agenda into Political Action. So first, I'd like to ask our moderator, Julia Scherf, to the stage. Julia has been leading the Asia Department at the Foundation here and is now the Deputy of the International Division. Hi, Julia. Cool. Yeah, and I think you're going to introduce the panelists and move through that first panel. I think you can take one of those. I pass it to you. Good morning, everybody. Please, who do I see? Ralf, come up on stage, please. And Jillian, who disappeared somewhere. Please come up. Katarzyna, where is she? I haven't seen her today. I saw her, I met her yesterday. Is she here? And Markus. Markus also must be somewhere. Oh, he's here. Great. So you're probably here. Good morning, everybody. I'm very pleased to be here and thanks, Jillian, for the very vivid and concrete introductory keynote session, keynote speech for this morning. We have an hour time to give examples and stories of these four activists in different stages of life present. We certainly will make sure that there is enough space for you, the audience, international guests, and also those who came from Berlin to be here today to give questions, comments, and answers to the panel. I'd like to first introduce who is sitting here with us. Katarzyna Szmieliewicz is from Poland. She's a human rights lawyer and activist. She co-founded the Panopticum Foundation, and this is an NGO working on surveillance issues and was very, very essential and crucial in the also successful anti-ACTA campaign in Poland. Thanks for being with us. Jillian was just introduced. Thanks again for being here from the States. Markus Beckerdahl is with the Digitale Gesellschaft, an organization which seems to be very, very present in this audience. Yesterday evening also it was people from Digitale Gesellschaft were everywhere. He founded New Thinking Communications GmbH in 2003, has been blogging since more than 10 years on Netzpolitik.org about politics in the digital society, and is an expert in the Enquete Commission, the study commission of the German Bundestag on Internet and Digital Society. Thanks for being here, Markus. Last but certainly not least, Ralf Fuchs. Ralf is the executive director of the Heinrich Böll Foundation, of the Green German Party, which is hosting this event. This is our building, our office, our headquarters, as we say, for the work we do internationally and nationally here in Germany. He has been in the executive board of the foundation since 1996 and is a long-standing Green Party activist, including stages of his life where he was a Green minister in the state government in Germany and also the co-president for the National Green Party. Ralf certainly has been working a long time also before the Internet even was born for political activism, so that makes it interesting to have you here. Thanks, Ralf. Let me start with the first round of questions on the issue of, again, how actually the possibility to do online protest changed your life and how it influenced the work you have been doing in your different spheres. I would like to start with Katarzyna again, who, as I mentioned before, was one of the key initiators in the anti-ACTA campaign in Poland in 2011. What kind of success, likelihood of success would have had the anti-ACTA campaign, Katarzyna, without the Internet? Tell us. Well, the question seems to be quite rhetorical, right? There would not be an ACTA campaign without Internet. We wouldn't even know about ACTA probably without Internet because for quite a while it was not an issue that people knew about. Very few people knew about that and the leaks about the text of ACTA, they started in the Internet. I mean, everything started there. I think we will talk later about that. I think we will talk later about the complicated dynamics between online and offline. I don't want to stress now that online is everything we should be doing and what has been done about ACTA because it wasn't the case. But certainly it was, I mean, there would be zero chance to do anything about ACTA without the Internet and on very different levels. So I already mentioned the leaks, so the fact that people cooperated internationally in gaining and sharing knowledge was the first stage. And sharing and sharing knowledge, nobody would know about the threat for the Internet. So that's the first stage. The second stage, of course, is mobilizing in the sense of telling people something is wrong, you should become more active. And that process with ACTA took years, years. I mean, there are many people in this room and I'm not really like the longest. My experience with fighting ACTA is not the longest one if I look at these rooms. I don't feel very comfortable about it. Misery thought tai edhi golane Bar-Yakta שלético, Ezra Barkassoun которых. K 설명 cette découverte était long. Black Ainette presirmere. bringing that issue to the broader audience. And only on that thing we started building our little campaigns step by step. Back then, two years ago, nobody really believed that it has any chance at all because it was so complicated, so technical, so chromatic that we thought, in Poland at least, that it's absolutely lost case. Nevertheless, we were doing our stuff and we were doing this online because it was easy, it was cheap. So we were producing documents, we were producing appeals, we were producing letters, which we would never do without internet because it would be simply too expensive to produce them and send them to people. Via internet, it was something we could have done without much effort. So we did, and we waited. And we thought the case is lost, and then SOPA and PIPA and Wikipedia protests came in the US, and that actually was triggered the whole attention in Poland. The attention of the people in Poland would not exist if it wasn't for a US case, which got communicated via internet. And only then so-called mass media, traditional media, picked it up. So again, we had internet being absolutely instrumental to bringing this issue to the broad attention of everybody in Poland. And then there was one weekend back in January 2012, right? I'm going confused with the date. When things happened so quickly, so quickly that nobody, including myself, would predict this. So we were ready with our letters of protest, with our idea how to appeal to MEPs in European Parliament. It was all on our website. And we informed media about the fact that Polish government is going to sign ACTA in a few days' time. And I thought it will be news for one day. It will be maybe news on the first page of one newspaper, but that's all. That was Friday. And over the weekend, I mean, we really had to bring emerging scenarios into play because suddenly our website, which is normally read by, I don't know, 10,000 people, it was blocked because of the traffic because everybody wanted to get ACTA, anti-ACTA appeals. And again, that kind of dynamics, that kind of network effect is only possible on the internet. And another step that was absolutely instrumental to the whole thing in Poland was what hackers did. So Polish international hackers, whatever, hacker community, wherever they were, I don't know, they started blocking governmental websites. And that was a serious form of online protest. That's how I saw it. The government said that's a terrorism. And when the government gave it the name of terrorism, people really get pissed off. And only then they moved to the streets. So there were so many steps which could have happened only online that brought people to the streets and triggered the whole political process. Thank you so much. Markus, Netzpolitik.org is the blog you have been attending to for the last 12 years, I believe. Tell us about how ACTA, for example, was also commented or pushed forward and how internationally also you are arguing and working on the blog. Yeah, Netzpolitik.org. I founded the first blog in 2002 and then the actual version in 2004. And it's not only my blog. We have up to 30 co-bloggers. Some of them are in the room, some not. We blogged the first time about ACTA in 2008 at a time where the first leaks appeared on the internet and nobody was really interested. There were only some days of interest in mass media when someone found out that it might be used to search on MP3 players at the borders for illegal copies. That was a big media hype for one day. But the day after, nobody took care about ACTA until a long time. And in 2010, there was, for us, we were still working on ACTA. Connected with lots of other people over European digital rights where Kasia is involved, Jeremy is involved, lots of other people are involved and internationally. But it was more a battleground in the European Parliament and it was important for us to go to this battleground in the European Parliament and to do lobbying and try to block ACTA where the decision should be made. And it definitely worked. Nobody of us expected that. It worked, but it worked that we had another two or three years that there was no decision. And I think the whole ACTA protest learned from a protest 10 years ago. It was the first time that there was a transnational European civil society organized only over the internet. It was a time in the fights against software patent. And when I heard your talk about the SOPA blackout day, I was wondering about the US view on this case because we started 10 years ago a blackout day on software patents, but outside of the Linux community and the digital rights community, which was very small at that time. Nobody took notice. But for us, it was, at that time, very important to use it. And at that time, we learned a lot about how the European Parliament works. And I think 10 years later, you take a look who was engaged in the ACTA protest on the battleground of the European Parliament. You saw most of them learned how a parliament works and how you do lobbying at the time on software patents. And we also learned how to organize the transnational European community to get involved. With ACTA, we only had the problem. Nobody took care. Nobody was interested. And then the Polish started jumping after the Americans blocked their websites. Yeah, and in Germany, we had an anonymous video and lots of people thought YouTube will be blocked tomorrow. So 100,000 people went to the street. And we were totally surprised. We organized a demonstration here in Berlin. We expected 600. We didn't really believe that 600 came, but we told the police 600 might come. And then on a cold Saturday like this, there were 10,000 people outside of the street. And most of them were younger than me. They could be my sons and daughters. But they thought they must watch television tomorrow if ACTA comes and blocks YouTube. And so they went to the streets. But as Kasia mentioned, we were prepared. We were prepared. And ACTA, nobody took care. But when people took notice, they could get information on our website. All these information gathered with 100 people maybe worldwide over the last years. And without the internet, it wouldn't have been possible. And without the internet, it wouldn't have been possible that we get 100,000 people on the streets within days in Germany without any central mobilization. It was totally decentral. Some demonstrations were organized by pirate parties, some by anonymous activists, some by 16-year-old school kids. Who did their first political action in their life. Some of them by Hellenistische Internationale and Digitale Gesellschaft in Berlin. So it was totally a grassroots movement only organized over blocks, Twitter, Facebook, and YouTube, of course. And this shows how it might work. The problem is, after ACTA, everybody asks us, what's the next ACTA? How can you mobilize them all again? And does it work for other topics as well? And we can only say, well, we don't know. We are working on digital rights issues. So we know how to use the internet. We have lots of experiences. If the internet is involved in a topic of regulation, then it's very easy to use the internet, to save the internet. But we don't know what it's about on other topics. Other activists on other topics must do their own experiences.
